WEBVTT

00:00:01.619 --> 00:00:04.280
Nikhil, Elvis, welcome to Talk Python, you guys.

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:06.300
Hey, it's great to be here.

00:00:07.100 --> 00:00:08.320
Yeah, it's awesome to have you here.

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:14.500
You're building some cool products, and Nikhil, you're back on the show.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:22.100
We spoke to you back in Salt Lake City at Startup Row,

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:24.780
and now your startup is more started,

00:00:25.060 --> 00:00:27.280
and I'm really excited to hear about it,

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:31.220
and that's what we're mostly going to focus on this episode,

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:33.880
talking about building Python web apps.

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:37.920
Normally when you say something like that,

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:41.080
a person who is not a web developer would go,

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:44.540
oh, you're building apps with Python, web apps with Python, that's cool.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:47.360
A web developer would be like, okay, what is that?

00:00:47.460 --> 00:00:52.180
That's Python, CSS, HTML, JavaScript, React, etc., SQL.

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:55.280
There's a lot going on normally,

00:00:55.520 --> 00:00:59.700
but we can winnow it down a little bit and have a little more focus.

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:03.240
When we say Python web apps, it's a little more like that, right?

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:04.440
Yeah, definitely.

00:01:04.530 --> 00:01:06.860
And I think a lot of people, when they hear Python web apps,

00:01:07.120 --> 00:01:09.340
they think of Django, Flask.

00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:11.520
They call themselves Python web frameworks,

00:01:11.630 --> 00:01:12.560
and they're really great frameworks.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.540
But like you mentioned, there's a lot of things that go into web development.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:18.160
There's front-end, back-end hosting, et cetera.

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:21.080
And when you think of frameworks like Django, Flask,

00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:23.800
they do a great job of handling the back-end, the database,

00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:25.260
the kind of connection layer.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:33.500
But like you mentioned, when you have to write the front end, you end up having to kind of go back to HTML, React, JavaScript, and the traditional tools.

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:42.660
And generally in web development, you'll set up your back end as kind of one service, your front end as one service, hook them up through some sort of API and develop through that.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:47.540
And it works great, but one part, like you mentioned, is there's a lack of unification.

00:01:48.320 --> 00:01:53.220
So when it comes to building an app, you have to piece together a front end, a back end, then figure out how to host it.

00:01:53.680 --> 00:02:02.200
So a really big part of why we started Reflex was to kind of simplify all these different layers of web development into one batteries included framework.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:09.979
And one of the biggest challenges along with the batteries included is having everything built in, but also keeping it flexible enough, right?

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:12.780
Because people want to do all sorts of stuff with their web apps.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:21.240
So that's really one of the main challenges that we faced going through all this was how can we make a framework that, you know, people can just get started, but it doesn't box them in.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.480
they can still make all the stuff they were going to make using their JavaScript apps.

00:02:25.050 --> 00:02:29.260
Right. That is the big challenge. And we're going to dive into that. You guys got some awesome stuff.

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:32.980
But before we do, maybe, you know, it's been two years or so since you've been on the show.

00:02:33.050 --> 00:02:37.000
Give a quick introduction, just who you are. How you got here?

00:02:37.700 --> 00:02:40.100
So, yeah, I'm Nikhil. I'm co-founder here at Reflex.

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:45.680
Last time we chatted was about a year and a half ago. At that time, our company name was Pinecone with a Y.

00:02:46.250 --> 00:02:50.600
That was at Startup Row. And our mission when we started, and even now,

00:02:50.680 --> 00:02:53.180
is to just simplify the whole process of web development

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:56.300
from front end, back end, hosting, all these parts,

00:02:56.360 --> 00:02:59.140
and make a framework that simplifies all these parts

00:02:59.140 --> 00:03:01.460
so a newcomer can easily share their ideas

00:03:01.680 --> 00:03:04.640
without getting all caught up in learning new tools,

00:03:04.840 --> 00:03:07.860
learning new languages, boilerplate, and all this.

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:10.460
So that's been our goal from the start.

00:03:10.660 --> 00:03:12.740
And maybe just some background on why

00:03:12.860 --> 00:03:14.120
we even came to this idea.

00:03:14.900 --> 00:03:16.660
So prior to working on this, I was

00:03:16.780 --> 00:03:19.000
working at a self-driving car startup,

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:20.100
and then I was working at Apple.

00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:23.120
And at both these roles, I was working on AI teams

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:24.920
with really talented engineers,

00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:26.560
but we were all Python engineers.

00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:30.120
So we could do anything with database, backend,

00:03:30.220 --> 00:03:31.720
all this stuff, but when it came to something

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:34.060
as simple as make a UI for this app,

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:35.680
make a dashboard to showcase this data,

00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:38.360
make a little form to submit it,

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:41.260
sometimes these senior engineers would be like,

00:03:41.340 --> 00:03:43.920
okay, that's not my domain, I can't do that in Python.

00:03:44.860 --> 00:03:46.600
- Sure, I have a PhD in machine learning,

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:48.820
but I can't build a website, so now what?

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:50.880
Exactly, and that's kind of where we are.

00:03:51.050 --> 00:03:55.980
And a big reason of that is if you think about, you know, different languages and their use cases,

00:03:56.290 --> 00:03:59.260
Python is used in so many, it's one of the most broad languages.

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:04.320
If you think about all the areas it's used, backend databases, AI, ML, all these areas.

00:04:04.590 --> 00:04:09.660
But there's really one place that it's not used traditionally, and that's kind of front-end development.

00:04:10.280 --> 00:04:12.000
And for there, like JavaScript is king.

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:17.160
And if you take the inverse of that and think about JavaScript, it's one of the most popular languages in the world, right?

00:04:17.380 --> 00:04:19.100
Like it's one, two, or three up there.

00:04:19.700 --> 00:04:23.700
And if you think about the use case for it, it's mostly all around web applications.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:27.640
So what we see, what we kind of notice is, you know, people love Python.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:29.940
They want to do all their work in Python when it's accessible.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:31.860
And people love web development.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:34.320
And they use JavaScript because they love web development.

00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:37.360
But there's not much usage of JavaScript outside that domain.

00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:42.080
So really our big focus was, well, can we fill in this gap in the Python ecosystem

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:46.240
where people are doing everything in Python and then suddenly this one domain of websites,

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:48.500
its front ends, that can't be handled.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:50.860
And they need to use a different tool,

00:04:50.990 --> 00:04:52.440
use a different language, outsource that.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:54.520
And that was a big thing we wanted to solve.

00:04:55.360 --> 00:04:57.280
The same people with the ideas, building the back end,

00:04:57.420 --> 00:04:59.220
building the AI, building the whatever it is,

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:02.300
should be also the people presenting it, building the UI

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:04.180
layer, and kind of sharing their ideas.

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:05.180
Yeah, absolutely.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:08.860
Many people I talk to would rather build everything in Python,

00:05:09.140 --> 00:05:11.660
but they end up piecing it together as they have to.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:13.780
Elvis, good to see you.

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:14.540
Yeah, same.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:15.500
Yeah.

