00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:34.580
All right, well, let's talk.

00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:38.780
We've introduced it a little bit, but Reflex.

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:44.740
I'll read the little, the H1, the H2 for you, and then we'll go from there.

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:49.780
It has that front end, back end, pure Python, and then the open source framework to build

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:52.120
and deploy web apps, no JavaScript required.

00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:54.120
There's a lot to unpack there.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:10:01.180
So tell people what Reflex is, and then we'll dig into the use cases and some of the open

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:02.180
source stuff and so on.

00:10:02.780 --> 00:10:07.880
Yeah, so like we kind of talked about earlier, Reflex is a Python framework to build web

00:10:08.020 --> 00:10:08.500
apps in Python.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:12.900
And it's an open source framework, so you don't have to sign up for a SaaS or do anything.

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:15.580
You just do pip install Reflex, kind of like what's shown at the bottom.

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:18.520
And you can start using it like any other Python library.

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:24.200
And like I mentioned, the key distinction that we're trying to do is kind of unify the whole

00:10:24.870 --> 00:10:25.220
web stack.

00:10:25.940 --> 00:10:29.580
So all the parts that normally go into web development, building a front end, building

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:34.900
a back end, connecting them, maybe including a database and then deploying it, usually these

00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:39.320
involve using several different tools, technologies, even often multiple languages.

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:42.380
And the overhead for that could be really high.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:47.939
So if you think about before, like a full-fledged web app, usually you're not going to do that

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:51.120
unless you have, you know, you have like a mission to do.

00:10:51.220 --> 00:10:53.020
Like you have something you're trying to make,

00:10:53.740 --> 00:10:55.000
you have it kind of specked out

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:57.380
and you're going to kind of invest that effort into it.

00:10:57.820 --> 00:11:00.260
It's very hard or most people aren't going to, you know,

00:11:00.540 --> 00:11:02.620
prototype a web app or kind of build out like that

00:11:02.720 --> 00:11:04.520
because the overhead needed is way too high

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:05.960
to kind of mess around with.

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:08.920
So what generally happens, especially for Python developers,

00:11:09.240 --> 00:11:12.120
is they'll use Python scripts, they'll use Jupyter notebooks.

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:14.380
And in the Python community also,

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:15.600
there's other pretty good frameworks,

00:11:16.400 --> 00:11:20.040
things like streamlit Gradio, which are also in the Python environment.

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:24.560
And I think try to target a very similar, problem that we're doing where, you

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:27.200
know, people have their data, people know Python and they want to showcase it.

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:31.700
So these are kind of the existing tools, that, that were there before we started.

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:35.960
And I think they all have their place to get started with, but they're very

00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:37.700
limiting and what you can build with them, right?

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:39.900
Like that's good for the most basic prototype.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:42.500
You can have a script, you can have a Jupyter notebook, but this is not

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:46.360
something necessarily you'd want to share within your team to build up to a

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:49.080
like usually once it becomes a bit more complex,

00:11:50.959 --> 00:11:52.620
you hand it off to another team,

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:55.500
or if you're brave, you go learn JavaScript or something.

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:57.500
But usually there's a point where it's like,

00:11:57.620 --> 00:11:58.400
"All right, I've done my job.

00:11:58.540 --> 00:12:00.760
Like someone else, like go make this production ready."

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:04.140
And a big part of what we're trying to do different at Reflex

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:06.360
is compared to other Python,

00:12:07.280 --> 00:12:09.140
and I'd even say other like non-JavaScript frameworks,

00:12:09.900 --> 00:12:12.920
is to keep everything in Python in one language,

00:12:13.260 --> 00:12:16.340
but without having any of these trade-offs

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:17.960
low code or no code platform.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:19.920
So usually low code and no code,

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:24.160
they exchange things like performance features,

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:26.300
things like that for usability.

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:27.280
- Customization.

00:12:28.519 --> 00:12:28.920
- Customization.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:31.840
So you can build a certain subset of apps,

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:35.380
but you need to kind of keep your aspirations confined

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:36.560
to what that framework's gonna give you.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:37.940
Like you want some random component,

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:39.140
you want a mapping component,

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:40.860
you have to hope that framework has it.

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:42.700
You want to integrate with a certain database,

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.820
you have to hope that they're gonna give you

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:45.300
that integration.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:48.120
So one of the very nice things about Python is,

00:12:49.160 --> 00:12:50.320
especially the backend integrations, right?

00:12:52.060 --> 00:12:54.260
