though you're coding it in Python, the front end will compile out to a Next.js app. The back end

00:18:42.540 --> 00:18:46.980
will compile out to a FastAPI back end that hook up together. So it's pretty much the same

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:51.380
architecture you would write as if you were writing it by hand. So there's no -- there's -- like,

00:18:51.440 --> 00:18:54.700
we're not taking a shortcut as in, like, if you were to write it by hand, it would actually compile.

00:18:55.080 --> 00:18:59.140
you would probably write an xjs front end fast api back end and connect it and we're kind of giving

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:04.400
a layer on top of that and by developing on top of react it goes back to this you know we don't

00:19:04.400 --> 00:19:09.340
want to reinvent the wheel web dev is a really mature ecosystem we're not going to be able to

00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:14.140
you know remake react and all the components out there so when we started our big approach was

00:19:14.560 --> 00:19:21.260
let's wrap react um and not only like our do our components rack wrap react but we make it very

00:19:21.280 --> 00:19:26.580
easy for developers to wrap their own components so kind of like what elvis said we have companies

00:19:27.100 --> 00:19:31.660
like fortune 100 companies that internally they have their own react you know component library

