00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:31.760
So if you go to reflex.dev and scroll down,

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:33.220
just have a page or something,

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:38.019
there's a little tab thing across the top here

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:40.480
that has how do you create a form?

00:39:40.820 --> 00:39:41.920
How do you create a chat bot?

00:39:42.320 --> 00:39:44.240
How do you create an image gen?

00:39:44.440 --> 00:39:46.020
And you know, this thing's pretty cool.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:46.900
It says, what do you want to see?

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:48.020
And all this stuff is live, right?

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:49.560
So I could write here and type, I want to see a bunny.

00:39:51.039 --> 00:39:55.920
And within just a moment, boom, there's a bunny running on,

00:39:57.980 --> 00:39:58.360
what was it?

00:39:59.080 --> 00:39:59.820
I don't remember where I saw it.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:01.800
Running on Flux, right?

00:40:02.140 --> 00:40:02.280
Yeah.

00:40:03.380 --> 00:40:04.220
Yeah, Flux, here it is.

00:40:05.519 --> 00:40:06.940
Fluxchnell, fast, the fast version.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:07.840
It's very fast.

00:40:07.900 --> 00:40:10.980
So it's pretty fast compared to--

00:40:10.980 --> 00:40:12.200
I was playing with Mid Journey yesterday,

00:40:12.440 --> 00:40:14.920
and that took a while, then a lot of 500 errors,

00:40:14.990 --> 00:40:16.460
and it took a while longer, then eventually I

00:40:16.460 --> 00:40:17.220
got a picture out of it.

00:40:19.040 --> 00:40:19.540
It's pretty cool.

00:40:19.680 --> 00:40:21.700
You got charts and so on.

00:40:23.059 --> 00:40:26.420
Let's maybe just talk about this little--

00:40:26.420 --> 00:40:28.700
send us a message, put your name, email, and message.

00:40:29.220 --> 00:40:31.860
What does it look like to code up one of these things?

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:36.000
Yeah, so basically, in all these examples you show,

00:40:36.160 --> 00:40:38.040
the code on the right is the entire code needed.

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:39.580
So it all fits in one file.

00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:41.660
Like there's no extra stuff you need beyond that.

00:40:41.730 --> 00:40:43.860
So if you were to copy that and run it in an app,

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:44.700
it would actually run.

00:40:45.540 --> 00:40:45.820
And--

00:40:45.840 --> 00:40:47.360
Yeah, just to get people listening,

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:52.140
there's probably 50 lines, 45 lines, something like that,

00:40:52.140 --> 00:40:52.460
a code.

00:40:53.070 --> 00:40:53.460
Yeah, OK.

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:57.260
And so one thing you'll notice is it's all in one language.

00:40:57.410 --> 00:40:58.740
And in this case, even one file.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:00.260
So it doesn't have to be in one file.

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:02.320
You can have multi-page, et cetera, reflex apps.

00:41:02.820 --> 00:41:05.079
But the kind of nice part is the front end and back end

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:06.720
can live together in one repository.

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:10.440
And so normally, people that have written front end,

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:13.060
they're probably used to either writing React HTML tags

00:41:13.150 --> 00:41:15.500
or templating through Jinja, et cetera.

00:41:16.380 --> 00:41:19.260
And what we kind of do different in Reflex

00:41:19.460 --> 00:41:22.260
is we define your front end as nothing but Python functions.

00:41:23.010 --> 00:41:25.760
So it fits in exactly with all the Python syntax.

00:41:25.810 --> 00:41:28.200
You don't have to kind of learn a new language there.

00:41:28.760 --> 00:41:29.740
Everything is a Python function.

00:41:29.810 --> 00:41:31.800
So for example, normally when you have a button,

00:41:32.570 --> 00:41:34.340
rather than writing an HTML button tag,

00:41:34.680 --> 00:41:36.980
we have built-in components like rx.button,

00:41:37.660 --> 00:41:39.220
which as you call it, will create a button.

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:42.900
And the kind of layout of the front end,

00:41:43.040 --> 00:41:44.720
if you've ever worked with React,

00:41:45.100 --> 00:41:47.200
it's very similar to React or even HTML

00:41:47.370 --> 00:41:49.640
in the sense that you have this nested tree structure

00:41:49.860 --> 00:41:52.320
that kind of maps directly to the HTML DOM.

00:41:53.360 --> 00:41:55.780
And within there, you can define all your UI components.

00:41:56.740 --> 00:41:58.480
So that kind of is how the front end works.

00:41:58.550 --> 00:41:59.800
And once you define your UI,

00:42:00.080 --> 00:42:02.620
these Python functions compile down to React app in the end.

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:07.180
Now, the interesting thing is how to make this interactive, right?

00:42:07.240 --> 00:42:08.160
Like, how do you add state to this?

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:12.140
So in this example, if you want to do a form or in the image generation, I really want

00:42:12.140 --> 00:42:16.320
to hook this up with my OpenAI or my mid-journey model to create something.

00:42:17.539 --> 00:42:21.400
So normally in web development, you end up having to write a front-end, a back-end, and

00:42:21.400 --> 00:42:26.560
a networking layer between the two where you set up a FastAPI endpoint for every single

00:42:26.740 --> 00:42:27.320
action you want.

00:42:27.690 --> 00:42:31.040
Then on the front-end, you're going to call that API, get the result by, parse it back,

00:42:31.070 --> 00:42:32.340
and then update your UI.

00:42:32.860 --> 00:42:35.320
So that's the normal flow of, say, even adding one new feature.

00:42:35.560 --> 00:42:38.160
Like if you want to add a button that generates an image and shows it,

00:42:38.560 --> 00:42:40.660
it will involve touching like multiple files,

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:42.500
going through all this stuff and hooking it together.

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:46.100
So one thing that we've done in Reflex beyond, you know,

00:42:46.660 --> 00:42:49.760
bringing it to one language is abstracting away the front end,

00:42:49.900 --> 00:42:51.400
back end networking layer.

00:42:51.960 --> 00:42:54.640
So in Reflex, you'll never have to write an API call.

00:42:54.650 --> 00:42:58.420
You never have to write a post request, a get request or any of that.

00:42:58.430 --> 00:42:59.660
All of that is done under the hood.

00:43:00.420 --> 00:43:06.800
So to set up your kind of state and interactive, you can do this all within what we call a

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:07.240
state class.

00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:10.320
So a state class is just a normal Python class.

00:43:10.500 --> 00:43:15.740
And within it, you define all the fields in your state that can change over time, which

00:43:15.740 --> 00:43:22.300
we call vars, as well as any event handlers that can change the vars.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:25.160
So an event handler is just a Python function or method.

00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:27.980
And I think the image gen is a good example of it.

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:32.160
So for example, in the image, the image URL is a var because it's something that's going

00:43:32.160 --> 00:43:32.620
to change.

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:39.320
And an event handler would be the getImage function, which is a function that when they

00:43:39.460 --> 00:43:42.080
hit submit on the input, we call it.

00:43:42.440 --> 00:43:48.040
So in order to hook up the frontend and backend, all you have to do is hook up the UI to the

00:43:48.120 --> 00:43:48.600
Python function.

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:52.820
So you can say button on click equals state dot getImage.

00:43:53.560 --> 00:43:58.700
And what this does under the hood is when you click that button, it creates an event, it

00:43:58.820 --> 00:44:02.960
sends up through a web socket to the backend, it will run your Python function on the backend.

00:44:03.780 --> 00:44:08.820
So whether that's your OpenAI, your Replicate, whatever it is, all of their state runs on

00:44:08.820 --> 00:44:09.760
the backend on the server.

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.000
And that's what allows us to keep the state in pure Python.

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:15.760
So it will update your state UI.

00:44:16.050 --> 00:44:19.560
In this case, it's going to update the image URL and send that back.

00:44:19.800 --> 00:44:24.340
And it works very similar to React in the sense that as your state updates, the front-end

00:44:24.580 --> 00:44:25.200
updates reactively.

00:44:27.020 --> 00:44:28.460
Yeah, that's super cool.

00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:31.860
Yeah, kind of just two-way data binding on the values there.

00:44:32.480 --> 00:44:33.280
Exactly, yeah.

00:44:34.460 --> 00:44:34.640
Yeah.

00:44:35.700 --> 00:44:41.320
All right, so you just said something interesting, that there's the Next.js React front-end and

00:44:41.320 --> 00:44:42.360
the FastAPI back-end.

00:44:42.860 --> 00:44:46.180
But you didn't say it's calling HTTP APIs.

00:44:46.320 --> 00:44:47.720
You said it's using WebSockets.

00:44:48.120 --> 00:44:48.520
Yes.

00:44:49.700 --> 00:44:55.040
What's the deal there? Why WebSockets and not Pydantic over HTTP or something?

00:44:56.080 --> 00:45:00.320
No, it's a really good question. And I think this is like, and a lot of people ask us, you know,

00:45:00.390 --> 00:45:04.700
how is Reflex's performance? Or what are the downsides of Reflex? Like, what's the catch?

00:45:04.790 --> 00:45:08.260
Because up to now, we've been saying, you know, we can perform, create anything you can do in

00:45:08.340 --> 00:45:14.300
JavaScript, anything you can do in React. So a lot of people are kind of asked about the performance.

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:19.980
And we kind of made design Reflex to be really performant in everything we do.

00:45:20.700 --> 00:45:27.080
And the reason we use WebSockets is because Reflex apps, especially like very stateful apps, often need to make a bunch of requests.

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:35.320
So rather than having to reestablish a new HTTP request every time, by keeping a WebSocket, we are really able to optimize the speed of the apps.

00:45:35.940 --> 00:45:42.180
So when you type your prompt, say you want a bunny, and you press enter.

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:44.600
I changed it to a fast bunny, by the way.

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:46.700
because you said the website was fast.

00:45:46.870 --> 00:45:47.720
Now we have a fast bunny.

00:45:48.030 --> 00:45:49.280
So when you want that fast bunny,

00:45:50.260 --> 00:45:51.920
it will create a little event that says,

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:54.340
hey, this guy wants to call get image

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:55.660
and he typed fast bunny.

00:45:56.380 --> 00:45:57.440
It'll take that little payload,

00:45:57.740 --> 00:45:58.620
send it through the web socket

00:45:58.960 --> 00:45:59.760
that's already been established,

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:02.280
run the Python function on the backend

00:46:02.600 --> 00:46:04.640
and then send only the state delta back.

00:46:05.060 --> 00:46:06.840
So for example, if you have a really large app

00:46:06.940 --> 00:46:08.660
with hundreds of pages and hundreds of states,

00:46:09.260 --> 00:46:10.620
changing this is not going to say,

00:46:11.040 --> 00:46:12.660
hey, front end, this is their entire new state.

00:46:12.770 --> 00:46:14.420
We only send the diffs and stuff back.

00:46:14.920 --> 00:46:15.860
over the web socket.

00:46:15.980 --> 00:46:19.040
So all of this was done in the name of performance

00:46:19.240 --> 00:46:20.960
and making Reflex app really snappy

00:46:21.160 --> 00:46:21.800
for whatever you're doing.

00:46:22.340 --> 00:46:22.900
Oh, interesting.

00:46:23.040 --> 00:46:26.660
So in a sense, the Python code that I write,

00:46:27.120 --> 00:46:28.560
even though there's this React bit,

00:46:29.160 --> 00:46:31.040
some of it still lives on the back end.

00:46:31.640 --> 00:46:31.800
Yeah.

00:46:32.300 --> 00:46:33.960
And then some of it gets kind of mirrored

00:46:34.100 --> 00:46:36.120
to React on the front end.

00:46:36.120 --> 00:46:36.500
Is that right?

00:46:37.040 --> 00:46:38.760
Yeah, and I think this is something,

00:46:39.180 --> 00:46:41.420
especially as people are learning Reflex,

00:46:41.520 --> 00:46:43.680
one of the things we try to emphasize most,

00:46:44.320 --> 00:46:46.900
which is, though it's all in one file, it's all in Python,

00:46:47.680 --> 00:46:50.400
there still is a distinction between the frontend and backend

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:53.060
because of this fact that the frontend compiles to Next.js app

00:46:53.580 --> 00:46:54.800
while the backend is a FastAPI.

00:46:55.560 --> 00:46:58.140
So in this case, it's pretty much all the UI code, right,

00:46:58.240 --> 00:46:59.940
like what's inside the index function.

00:47:00.260 --> 00:47:01.740
That's your Next.js React app.

00:47:02.660 --> 00:47:05.640
Your FastAPI is pretty much your state and your event handlers.

00:47:06.260 --> 00:47:08.520
So within there, you can keep everything in pure Python,

00:47:08.820 --> 00:47:09.720
use anything you want.

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:12.859
The one thing you can't do and we can't do

00:47:12.800 --> 00:47:14.860
is compile arbitrary Python to JavaScript.

00:47:15.340 --> 00:47:18.240
So that's the reason all the event handlers run on the server.

00:47:18.500 --> 00:47:20.460
So you can use any library, anything you want.

00:47:20.980 --> 00:47:24.220
And on the front end, we only compile kind of a static website.

00:47:24.700 --> 00:47:26.840
So there's no logic that ever happens on the front end,

00:47:27.040 --> 00:47:27.120
actually.

00:47:27.800 --> 00:47:28.720
Yeah, OK.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:31.440
Just updating the bindings and triggering events.

00:47:31.480 --> 00:47:33.060
The front end is just like a dumb UI.

00:47:33.320 --> 00:47:34.480
It's like, give me the state.

00:47:34.540 --> 00:47:35.260
I'm going to show the state.

00:47:36.260 --> 00:47:36.660
OK.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:38.960
Well, that's definitely a nice bunny.

00:47:39.800 --> 00:47:42.600
So one thing that I think is notable here,

00:47:42.780 --> 00:47:44.740
and I've seen this in other frameworks as well.

00:47:45.000 --> 00:47:52.500
For example, I had PewPy on Talk Python recently,

00:47:52.720 --> 00:47:56.400
which is also sort of React stuff on the front end.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:48:02.980
But this is a lot more, PewPy is more running,

00:48:03.180 --> 00:48:09.220
I think, React type stuff almost in PyScript, I believe.

00:48:11.100 --> 00:48:12.220
which is interesting, right?

00:48:12.680 --> 00:48:14.940
But one of the things that I think you find with a lot of these

00:48:15.840 --> 00:48:21.960
is the shape of the code matches the DOM a lot of times

00:48:21.980 --> 00:48:27.280
or at least the conceptual idea of the hierarchy of the UI, right?

00:48:27.680 --> 00:48:31.240
So for example, here you've got a VStag with a skeleton with a flex

00:48:32.080 --> 00:48:34.580
and then you start putting forms and in the form

00:48:34.660 --> 00:48:37.200
and all of this, every word that I said there

00:48:37.200 --> 00:48:38.619
is another level of indentation

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:40.840
and then you indent and you get a React input and a React button

00:48:40.890 --> 00:48:43.660
and you unindent Python style.

00:48:45.180 --> 00:48:47.660
And I think it makes it pretty easy to think about,

00:48:48.220 --> 00:48:49.560
here's the code, here's the UI,

00:48:49.810 --> 00:48:53.420
because the shape of the code matches the concept.

00:48:53.550 --> 00:48:55.560
It mirrors the UI in some ways,

00:48:56.120 --> 00:49:01.340
rather than just pure top to bottom imperative

00:49:01.430 --> 00:49:02.720
or just generating the UI,

00:49:02.930 --> 00:49:04.820
but actually the way it's structured,

00:49:05.430 --> 00:49:07.960
kind of like Flutter, it looks like it matches it.

00:49:08.060 --> 00:49:13.440
now yeah so i think there's kind of two approaches people in this space have taken to building like

00:49:13.540 --> 00:49:18.020
one is imperative which is kind of what you said and i think for example streamlit has taken this

00:49:18.060 --> 00:49:23.280
approach where to do a button you do you would do like st heading st button and it will implicitly

00:49:23.400 --> 00:49:28.500
like kind of magically put it into its thing and i think it could be good for simple stuff but it's

00:49:28.620 --> 00:49:32.720
really hard to reason about as your thing gets larger because you have to kind of contextualize

00:49:32.800 --> 00:49:37.480
wait has this been called already like what order is everything going is the button in this group or

00:49:37.420 --> 00:49:38.380
or is it outside of the group?

00:49:38.640 --> 00:49:39.940
Yeah, stuff like that, right?

00:49:40.200 --> 00:49:42.260
Yeah, so I think it's nice in some sense,

00:49:42.380 --> 00:49:44.280
but I don't think it scales very well,

00:49:44.840 --> 00:49:45.840
especially conceptually.

00:49:46.200 --> 00:49:47.420
It's hard to kind of reason about

00:49:48.300 --> 00:49:50.860
what all you've kind of built.

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:54.000
So I think, I guess going back

00:49:54.160 --> 00:49:55.180
to why it's in this structure,

00:49:56.600 --> 00:49:58.160
this is already kind of the natural structure

00:49:58.300 --> 00:49:59.420
from HTML, from React.

00:50:00.140 --> 00:50:01.500
And I think a lot of,

00:50:01.720 --> 00:50:02.640
as we were going through stuff

00:50:03.420 --> 00:50:04.560
related to API design,

00:50:05.220 --> 00:50:07.440
We try to improve the API where we can,

00:50:07.700 --> 00:50:08.580
but a lot of the times we realize,

00:50:08.700 --> 00:50:10.560
you know, the people that did it originally had a good idea,

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:12.220
and there's a reason.

00:50:12.260 --> 00:50:12.840
It's kind of the standard.

00:50:13.720 --> 00:50:14.580
Yeah, for sure.

00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:18.200
I think it takes a little getting used to, to be honest,

00:50:18.600 --> 00:50:21.040
to see such nested stuff, but I do like it.

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:21.600
I think it's good.

00:50:22.400 --> 00:50:24.740
Yeah, and I think part of it, I think in this example,

00:50:24.820 --> 00:50:26.780
we kind of nested it just to show it's all in one function,

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:28.200
but in a more practical setting,

00:50:28.260 --> 00:50:29.820
you would break this up into different components.

00:50:30.420 --> 00:50:31.360
So similar to React,

00:50:31.540 --> 00:50:33.220
you probably wouldn't have a giant nested thing,

00:50:33.540 --> 00:50:35.460
And you can think of each of those things as units

00:50:35.550 --> 00:50:36.200
that you work with.

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:36.760
Yeah.

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:40.460
Also, decorators help a lot with making

00:50:40.650 --> 00:50:43.140
dynamic components on the fly in terms of functionality.

00:50:44.200 --> 00:50:44.600
Yeah.

00:50:45.580 --> 00:50:47.300
All right, let's talk about just a couple more things

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:48.320
while we're here.

00:50:49.820 --> 00:50:51.980
I want to talk about the components.

00:50:52.380 --> 00:50:54.620
And the components are these building block pieces.

00:50:55.180 --> 00:50:56.460
Maybe pick just a couple you think

00:50:56.600 --> 00:50:57.840
highlight the idea of these things,

00:50:57.910 --> 00:50:58.720
and we can talk about them.

00:50:59.040 --> 00:51:02.199
Yeah, so I guess a really big thing people use this for

00:51:02.220 --> 00:51:04.020
is kind of like tables and graphing.

00:51:04.120 --> 00:51:06.000
So maybe if you go down to the table section,

00:51:08.140 --> 00:51:09.860
the AG Grid one might be a good one.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:12.000
So this is actually a good example of a third party

00:51:12.160 --> 00:51:12.400
component.

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:15.180
So you can see we have our built-in components,

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:20.260
but a lot of our enterprise users really wanted this AG Grid

00:51:20.380 --> 00:51:23.120
feature, which is one of the most popular table libraries.

00:51:23.680 --> 00:51:25.160
So we make it really easy.

00:51:25.280 --> 00:51:27.580
This is an example of a third party library someone's wrapped

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:29.180
that you can kind of bring in.

00:51:29.980 --> 00:51:32.640
And this is an easy way to kind of showcase your data.

00:51:32.760 --> 00:51:35.040
So a lot of data scientists, et cetera, use this library.

00:51:35.260 --> 00:51:39.780
It can hook up with your data frames and kind of show this.

00:51:39.860 --> 00:51:42.180
So this is another example showcasing kind of the flexibility

00:51:42.620 --> 00:51:45.380
of you want that random React library, even if it's not

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:48.700
in Reflex, like the team or external contributor

00:51:48.980 --> 00:51:50.360
often wraps this easily.

00:51:51.680 --> 00:51:55.600
And yeah, the kind of nice part about it is it's more high level.

00:51:55.660 --> 00:51:57.640
It has a lot of these built-in features like pagination,

00:51:57.880 --> 00:51:58.960
searching, sorting, and all these.

00:51:59.680 --> 00:52:02.100
So, you know, I think it's this balance, right?

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:03.820
Like we can give people the raw components.

00:52:03.980 --> 00:52:06.260
Like you can code everything in HTML.

00:52:06.820 --> 00:52:08.580
You can build everything from the ground up yourself,

00:52:09.280 --> 00:52:10.980
or you can use this kind of high level thing.

00:52:11.500 --> 00:52:15.740
And the nice part about Reflex is you can kind of approach it at any level that you want.

00:52:16.240 --> 00:52:18.820
So it's like, I want this nice built-in thing that has sorting pagination.

00:52:19.460 --> 00:52:19.840
Here it is.

00:52:20.380 --> 00:52:22.700
Or you're like, you know, I'm just going to build everything from the ground up.

00:52:22.700 --> 00:52:23.800
I want my own table component.

00:52:24.300 --> 00:52:25.580
We also give you the tools to do that.

00:52:26.020 --> 00:52:32.860
So I think it just kind of shows the scale at which you can kind of pick your level of abstraction as you're using it.

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:41.280
Yeah, then you just pip install the name of the thing and then just use it like a native component, right?

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:44.860
Exactly, and it will act like all other reflex components.

00:52:44.940 --> 00:52:48.260
So there's nothing distinct between our components and something you would wrap yourself.

00:52:49.260 --> 00:52:57.320
So if I was a reasonably sized company with a team of maybe many of them knowing React,

00:52:57.780 --> 00:53:02.640
it might make sense for me to build out an internal library of widgets that we use on our app

00:53:03.080 --> 00:53:04.640
and plug in to reflect something like that.

00:53:05.180 --> 00:53:05.280
Definitely.

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:11.080
And to that point, we have a whole guide on our website on wrapping React with different examples.

00:53:11.720 --> 00:53:16.980
And we're trying to make it accessible for Python developers because that's our user at the end.

00:53:17.040 --> 00:53:22.120
right so we wanted to make it accessible for even a non-javascript non-react expert to be able to

00:53:22.130 --> 00:53:26.740
wrap these components so we've seen in uh different companies like i kind of mentioned earlier that

00:53:26.840 --> 00:53:32.160
have their internal you know component systems in react a python developer was easily able to kind

00:53:32.160 --> 00:53:37.740
of wrap these because we make it super easy to wrap as just a python class where you just define

00:53:37.790 --> 00:53:44.260
the props so maybe if you go to the wrapping react section on the left hand side um it's kind of at

00:53:44.140 --> 00:53:51.200
the oh maybe go back to the main docs section but um yeah we try to make it really easy to bring

00:53:51.260 --> 00:53:56.060
your own components as well so whether you already have one or you want to make your own so this is

00:53:56.100 --> 00:54:00.000
like a spline one and you can see all you have to do is list all the props it's a python class

00:54:00.860 --> 00:54:04.920
you kind of have to just go find what library what npm library you're using list all the props

00:54:05.500 --> 00:54:08.839
and for interactive ones you may have to define that and then you can start using it right away

00:54:09.960 --> 00:54:11.840
Nice, so as part of your component,

00:54:11.870 --> 00:54:16.200
you define just basically the npm thing to install or whatever,

00:54:16.350 --> 00:54:17.100
and then off it goes.

00:54:17.470 --> 00:54:19.480
Yeah, and Reflex will install the component,

00:54:19.590 --> 00:54:21.620
it will wrap it for you, and it will compile out for you.

00:54:22.480 --> 00:54:23.200
Yeah, very cool.

