Where are we going?

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:36.840
- Awesome, so recently we just released Reflect 0.6

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:41.420
last month, and right now we're going after 0.7.

00:58:41.560 --> 00:58:44.760
So a big part of 0.7 is cleaning up a lot

00:58:44.850 --> 00:58:46.420
of our core components that we have,

00:58:46.640 --> 00:58:49.300
especially for the features people use the most.

00:58:49.580 --> 00:58:51.940
So the ones we're starting off with are,

00:58:53.040 --> 00:58:54.300
like you can see here, AG Grid Support,

00:58:54.520 --> 00:58:55.560
which is a big thing people ask,

00:58:55.740 --> 00:58:57.660
and beyond that just like very good support

00:58:57.980 --> 00:59:01.580
with tables, databases, and graphing

00:59:01.600 --> 00:59:03.680
a lot of these internal apps and data science use cases.

00:59:04.819 --> 00:59:07.060
Beyond that, one really important thing

00:59:07.580 --> 00:59:09.560
for web frameworks that we're trying to build is auth,

00:59:09.780 --> 00:59:10.440
so built in auth.

00:59:10.620 --> 00:59:12.820
So if anyone's ever used Django,

00:59:13.400 --> 00:59:14.820
they have a really great kind of way

00:59:14.980 --> 00:59:16.480
that you can plug any auth system in.

00:59:17.200 --> 00:59:19.300
And that's often the first thing someone wants

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:20.400
in a practical web app, right?

00:59:20.540 --> 00:59:21.920
They're like, I have, especially a data app,

00:59:22.540 --> 00:59:23.620
they're like, I have this great app,

00:59:23.660 --> 00:59:25.420
but I don't want anyone to be able to access it.

00:59:25.820 --> 00:59:27.380
And we already have integrations

00:59:27.500 --> 00:59:28.660
with third party auth providers,

00:59:29.380 --> 00:59:31.820
But we want to bring in just like first party auth

00:59:31.920 --> 00:59:32.980
where you can just add a click of a button,

00:59:33.330 --> 00:59:34.940
your website is going to have auth at this point.

00:59:36.270 --> 00:59:37.940
A lot of these, the other stuff here

00:59:38.160 --> 00:59:40.720
is related to a lot of performance improvements

00:59:40.830 --> 00:59:41.440
that we're going to make.

00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:46.360
So one key feature of Reflex is the development experience.

00:59:46.590 --> 00:59:48.380
So one part of that is code, but the other part

00:59:48.620 --> 00:59:51.380
is things like hot reload and how fast is it for me

00:59:51.380 --> 00:59:53.380
to actually make iterations on what I'm doing.

00:59:54.040 --> 00:59:56.600
So a lot of these other tickets are internal changes

00:59:56.620 --> 00:59:58.560
we're gonna do to make it easier for,

00:59:59.780 --> 01:00:01.220
pretty much improve the hot reload times.

01:00:01.380 --> 01:00:04.040
So we wanted people to improve their iteration speed a lot.

01:00:04.480 --> 01:00:06.060
A lot of time, people,

01:00:06.320 --> 01:00:07.880
like pretty much all their time should be spent

01:00:08.320 --> 01:00:10.180
looking at actions and coding and not waiting for anything.

01:00:11.100 --> 01:00:14.140
And then one final thing related to kind of

01:00:14.660 --> 01:00:16.940
how we wanna simplify the approach of UI and state

01:00:17.700 --> 01:00:20.760
is we're implementing a system called CSR,

01:00:21.040 --> 01:00:23.820
which is kind of, right now, I kind of mentioned

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:25.940
there's this difference between compile time and runtime.

01:00:26.740 --> 01:00:28.740
And there's certain things, your entire UI

01:00:28.920 --> 01:00:30.680
kind of needs to be known at compile time.

01:00:31.280 --> 01:00:32.420
So you have to compile your code,

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:33.660
and that's what you get at runtime.

01:00:34.620 --> 01:00:36.700
And what we're introducing is this idea

01:00:36.840 --> 01:00:39.280
of dynamic components, which are dynamics generated

01:00:39.480 --> 01:00:39.880
at runtime.

01:00:40.540 --> 01:00:42.480
So this will enable a really cool use cases.

01:00:43.160 --> 01:00:45.620
For example, you can have a chat bot that instead of just

01:00:45.780 --> 01:00:47.520
returning text all the time, it could return components.

01:00:47.680 --> 01:00:48.460
So it could return a graph.

01:00:48.580 --> 01:00:50.640
It could return a whole reflex page.

01:00:51.080 --> 01:00:53.800
And these could be components that you don't know upfront

01:00:53.820 --> 01:00:54.860
actually generated during runtime.

01:00:55.480 --> 01:00:57.540
So it's going to help a lot in terms of flexibility

01:00:58.260 --> 01:01:01.300
and also in terms of the ease of use in using Reflex.

01:01:01.460 --> 01:01:03.880
Because since they're generated at runtime,

01:01:04.020 --> 01:01:05.120
you can now use pure Python.

01:01:05.220 --> 01:01:06.280
You don't have any limitations.

01:01:06.600 --> 01:01:09.420
And there's a lot of advantages on the developer side as well.

01:01:09.980 --> 01:01:10.740
Yeah, that's very cool.

